We can begin to building models. Below, you can see the code for Website Journey Approach.

With this approach, we would like to describe one of the journeys of a customer from his/her entrance to the website to the purchase.

Step 1 â Data: In this approach, we decided to use fully clean reduced data we generated and communicated in this paperâs descriptive analysis part. The data has no missing values or inconsistency between parameters. Also, we have created subsets for each product to obtain individual predictions in the end. We believed that in this way, we could increase accuracy significantly.

Step 2 â Predicting Independent Variables: We selected Trendyol Visits, Category Visit, Price, and Visit Count as our independent variables and predicted them as follows:

â¢ Trendyol Visits (TY): We created a table including Date, TY Visit, and added 6 days prior and 1 day prior columns data next to it. Then, used the Linear Regression method to predict tomorrow.

â¢ Category Visit (CV): We calculated the historical mean of the Category Visit/TY Visit Ratio and used it in the prediction of tomorrow for Category Visit.

â¢ Price (P): Used last data point as a prediction of tomorrow.

â¢ Visit Count: Used TY, CV, and P variables, built Linear Regression model, and predicted tomorrow.

Step 3 â Predicting the Sold Count:

â¢ Linear Regression: We build a Linear Regression model with all predictors above and predicted tomorrow.

â¢ Conversion Ratio: We calculated the historical mean of the Visit Count/TY Visit Ratio and used it in the prediction of tomorrow for Category Visit.

  1. Product Page Approach With this approach, we would like to describe the journey of the customer from the product page to his/her purchase. Therefore, we have used Visit Count, Favored Count, and Basket Count independent variables.

Step 1 â Data: Time Series Approach: The same clean data we used in previous approaches.

Step 2 â Predicting Independent Variables: We have predicted these variables in two different ways. First, we built the Linear Regression model with their 6-day and 1-day prior data as we did before for all variables individually. Second, we predicted each of them with the ARIMA model built on their last 15-day data.

Step 3 â Predicting the Sold Count: We build the Linear Regression and randomForest models on these variables. Then, we used their predicted values of the predictors to forecast sold count for tomorrow.

  1. Time Series Approach In this approach, we have used ARIMA (Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average) method to predict the day after the last instance.

Step 1 â Data: The same data in Approach 1.

Step 2 â Predicting Independent Variables:

â¢ None (1): First, we did not use any predictor.

â¢ Visit Count (2): We built the ARIMA model on its last 15-day visit count data to predict the day after.

Step 3 â Predicting the Sold Count:

â¢ ARIMA (1): We built the ARIMA model on its last 15-day sold count data to predict the day after.

â¢ Conversion Ratio (2): We calculated the historical mean of conversion ratio (Visit Count/Sold Count). Then used this ratio to predict the day after.

## Approach 2 View Count to Sold Count Conversion Ratio-----
require(xts)

time_index <- seq(from = as.POSIXct("2020-06-24"), 
                  to = as.POSIXct("2020-07-08"), by = "day")
str(time_index)

#Fakir----
last2week_fakir_visitcount=tail(data_fakir$visit_count, n=15)
datavisitcount_fakir <- xts(last2week_fakir_visitcount, order.by = time_index)
visitcount_model_fakir=auto.arima(datavisitcount_fakir)
forecast_visitcount_fakir=forecast(visitcount_model_fakir,h=1)

arima_visitcount_fakir=as.data.table(arima_visitcount_fakir)

#Using historical conversion ratio mean to predict sold_count
conversion_arima_fakir_sold_count=(mean(data_fakir$sold_count/(data_fakir$visit_count)))*arima_visitcount_fakir

#Tayt----
last2week_tayt_visitcount=tail(data_tayt$visit_count, n=15)
datavisitcount_tayt <- xts(last2week_tayt_visitcount, order.by = time_index)

colnames(arima_visitcount_tayt) <- "31515569"

#Using historical conversion ratio mean to predict sold_count
conversion_arima_tayt_sold_count=(mean(data_tayt$sold_count/(data_tayt$visit_count)))*arima_visitcount_tayt

  1. Willingness Approach 1

In this approach, we decided to make 2 main changes. We decided to decrease the number of predictors and this enabled us to make the second change: Increasing the data size. In this approach, we have used Favored Count and Visit Count independent variables.

Step 1 â Data: All instances with non-zero favored_count and visit_count value. In this way, we achieved to increase data size by 50%.

Step 2 â Predicting Independent Variables: We built the Linear Regression model by using these independent variablesâ 6-day and 1-day prior data as predictors.

Step 3 â Predicting the Sold Count: We built the Linear Regression and randomForest models on the data. Then, we used their predicted values to forecast sold count.

##Fakir--------
#Input Variables
lm_visitfav_visit_count_fakir = visitfav_full_data_fakir %>% select (4)
lm_visitfav_visit_count_fakir [,lag_1:=shift(visit_count,1)]
lm_visitfav_visit_count_fakir [,lag_6:=shift(visit_count,6)]
lm_visitfav_visit_count_fakir =lm_visitfav_visit_count_fakir  [complete.cases(lm_visitfav_visit_count_fakir )]

fit_lm_visitfav_visit_count_fakir=lm(visit_count~.-1, data=lm_visitfav_visit_count_fakir)

yyy <- coef(fit_lm_visitfav_visit_count_fakir)
yyy=as.data.table(yyy)
coef_lm_visitfav_visit_count_fakir_lag6=yyy[1]
coef_lm_visitfav_visit_count_fakir_lag1=yyy[2]
visitfav_visit_count_fakir_pred=first(tail(lm_visitfav_visit_count_fakir$visit_count))*coef_lm_visitfav_visit_count_fakir_lag6+coef_lm_visitfav_visit_count_fakir_lag1*last(tail(lm_visitfav_visit_count_fakir$visit_count))
colnames(visitfav_visit_count_fakir_pred)= "visit_count"

lm_visitfav_favored_count_fakir = visitfav_full_data_fakir %>% select (5)
lm_visitfav_favored_count_fakir [,lag_1:=shift(favored_count,1)]
lm_visitfav_favored_count_fakir [,lag_6:=shift(favored_count,6)]
lm_visitfav_favored_count_fakir =lm_visitfav_favored_count_fakir [complete.cases(lm_visitfav_favored_count_fakir)]

coef_lm_visitfav_favored_count_fakir_lag1=yyy[2]

colnames(visitfav_favored_count_fakir_pred)= "favored_count"

willingness_lm_fakir_pred=as.data.table(willingness_lm_fakir_pred)

willingness_lm_fakir_pred

  1. Willingness Approach 2

In our final approach, we further simplified the model and increased the data size. Since we have seen that Basket Count variable has the strongest relationship with the Sold Count, we only used it on this approach.

Step 1 â Data: All instances with non-zero basket_count value. In this way, we achieved to further increase data size by 20%.

Step 2 â Predicting Independent Variables: We have used 2 techniques to predict the independent variable for the day after the last instance. First, we built the Linear Regression model by using its 6-day and 1-day prior data as predictors and completed the prediction of the basket_count. Second, we built the ARIMA model on its last 15-day data and completed its prediction.

Step 3 â Predicting the Sold Count: We built Linear Regression and randomForest models on the data we obtained in Step 1. Then, we used the predicted values we obtained Step 2 to forecast sold count.
